 in spring was 46 (20&#x02013;59); in summer 39 (20&#x02013;59); in autumn/winter 44 (22&#x02013;59), p&#x02009;=&#x02009;0.022. Median age did not differ between patients recruited in spring and autumn/winter (p&#x02009;=&#x02009;0.67).</p></sec><sec><title>Associations with self-reported depression</title><p>MSC &#x02265;9.3&#x000a0;nmol/L (AOR 4.4), HbA1c &#x0003e;70&#x000a0;mmol/L (&#x0003e;8.6%) (AOR 4.2) and antidepressants (AOR 4.9) were independently associated with self-reported depression (Table&#x000a0;<xref ref-type="table" rid="T5">5</xref>).</p><table-wrap position="float" id="T5"><label>Table 5</label><caption><p>Associations with self-reported depression for 181 patients with type 1 diabetes</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups" border="1"><colgroup><col align="left"/><col align="center"/><col align="center"/><col align="center"/><col align="center"/></colgroup><thead valign="top"><tr><th align="left" valign="bottom">&#x000a0;<hr/></th><th colspan="4" align="center" valign="bottom"><bold>Self-reported depression</bold><hr/></th></tr><tr><th align="left">&#x000a0;</th><th align="center"><bold>COR (95% CI)</bold></th><th align="center"><bold>P</bold><sup>
